## Key Points

The "1+2" link formula is obsolete: Trying to hide a commercial link by adding two random "natural" links to make it look balanced is a massive red flag. Top-tier sites (like TechCrunch) naturally have 12 to 50 links per page, while spammy guest posts usually cap out at 3 or 4.

Use AI to predict natural link placement: Dan fine-tuned a machine learning model (DeBERTa) on top-tier blogs to predict exactly where links naturally fall in text. If your commercial link doesn't land in a "natural" spot according to the model, you need to rewrite the content.

The "Penguin" test: Dan built a secondary AI model specifically to act as a web spam evaluator. If his model can easily detect which link on the page is the commercial one, the link is too obvious and shouldn't be published.

Gemini auto-links known brands: If you are a recognized entity and get an unlinked brand mention on a page, Google’s Gemini AI will often automatically turn that mention into a clickable link in AI Overviews.

You need a KG MID: To get those AI "gift" links, you must be in Google's Knowledge Graph (having a Knowledge Graph Machine ID). You can check your entity status using tools like the one on don.ai/tools.

Wikidata is a goldmine for semantic SEO: Dan downloaded the entire 68GB Wikidata dataset and built a semantic search engine using vector embeddings. This allows you to see exactly how AI models "think" about the relationships between your brand and specific concepts, which is incredible for keyword clustering and link building.

